{"id":"0802.4329","submitter":"Paolo Marconcini","authors":"P. Marconcini, M. Macucci, G. Iannaccone, B. Pellegrini","title":"Quantum analysis of shot noise suppression in a series of tunnel\n  barriers","comments":"This paper has been replaced with a new version (4 pages, 4 figures)","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 79, 241307(R) (2009)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.79.241307","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We report the results of an analysis, based on a straightforward\nquantum-mechanical model, of shot noise suppression in a structure containing\ncascaded tunneling barriers. Our results exhibit a behavior that is in sharp\ncontrast with existing semiclassical models for this particular type of\nstructure, which predict a limit of 1/3 for the Fano factor as the number of\nbarriers is increased. The origin of this discrepancy is investigated and\nattributed to the presence of localization on the length scale of the mean free\npath, as a consequence of the strictly 1-dimensional nature of disorder, which\ndoes not create mode mixing, while no localization appears in common\nsemiclassical models. We expect localization to be indeed present in practical\nsituations with prevalent 1-D disorder, and the existing experimental evidence\nappears to be consistent with such a prediction.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 29 Feb 2008 06:35:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 5 Mar 2008 15:22:11 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 8 Mar 2008 16:53:08 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 24 Dec 2008 17:05:37 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Fri, 3 Jul 2009 08:56:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-05-29"}
